threats.label: Error in use

threats.description: A person or entity denies being involved in an exchange with a third party or carrying out an operation.

threats.label: Illegal processing of data

threats.label: Malware infection

threats.label: Disclosure

threats.label: Breach of personnel availability

threats.label: Destruction of equipment or supports

threats.label: Fire

threats.label: Major accident

threats.label: Pollution
threats.description: Presence of dust, vapours, corrosive or toxic gases in the ambient air.

Information to be provided as a minimum:

 - The intention to transfer personal data to a third country or to an international organization
 - The retention period of the data or the criteria used to determine this duration

recommendations.description: Train all user to good practices in Cybersecurity.
recommendations.comment: The HR team should organize regular training sessions on password management, phishing awareness, and safe internet browsing. Documentation of the training should be maintained.

recommendations.description: Change the location of the backup to be offsite, and in a place more secure.
recommendations.comment: The IT manager should arrange for secure, offsite storage for backups, ensuring they are encrypted. This process should be documented and regularly audited for security compliance.

recommendations.description: Run the antivirus program at least once per week to check any threat.
recommendations.comment: The IT administrator should schedule weekly automatic antivirus scans on all devices. A report should be generated and reviewed to address any identified threats.

recommendations.description: Ensure the rules describes all the place that shouldn't be access by anyone.
recommendations.comment: The security manager should update access policies, defining restricted areas both physically and digitally, and communicate this clearly to all staff.

recommendations.description: Add as soon as possible a 2FA mean anywhere it is possible.
recommendations.comment: The system administrator should implement two-factor authentication (2FA) on all critical systems. This can be done through configuration settings and should be enforced for access to sensitive systems and data.

recommendations.description: Train the user to use all necessary software and hardware they use.
recommendations.comment: The IT department should conduct sessions or provide materials on how to use company-provided software and hardware efficiently. This should include troubleshooting and best practices.

recommendations.description: Check the contract with the third parties to ensure the NDA correspond to the needs.
recommendations.comment: The legal team should review and update third-party contracts to ensure NDAs are comprehensive and align with the company’s data protection policies.

recommendations.description: Change the permission of the backup software so the user cannot change any options.
Update the IT Charter so the user are aware of what they should do in each case.
recommendations.comment: The IT manager should review and update the IT Charter, ensuring it covers essential procedures and is communicated to all employees. Include clear guidelines for common issues like phishing or unauthorized access.

recommendations.description: Repeat the trainings at least once each year.
recommendations.comment: The HR team should schedule annual refresher training on cybersecurity and software/hardware usage. Participation should be tracked, and knowledge assessed through testing.

recommendations.description: Describe in the IT Charter how to manage user's equipment.
recommendations.comment: The IT manager should outline proper use, maintenance, and security measures for company devices in the IT Charter, ensuring employees know how to handle and report equipment issues.

recommendations.description: Test the efficiency of the training through exercises.
recommendations.comment: The IT manager should arrange periodic cybersecurity drills, such as simulated phishing attempts, to test employee responses. Feedback should be provided based on the results.

recommendations.description: Add good practices and rules concerning the password management in the IT Charter.
recommendations.comment:
The best practices should at least include:
- Number of characters
- Diversity of characters
- Renewal period
- Method of storage

recommendations.description: Log all event that happen on the computers.
recommendations.comment: The IT administrator should configure logging software to track user activities, software changes, and security events. Regular reviews of these logs are essential to identify any unusual activity.

recommendations.description: Close all doors that shouldn't be accessible by key or badge.
recommendations.comment: The facility manager should ensure that physical security measures, such as locks or badge access, are in place for all restricted areas. Regular checks should be conducted to maintain security.

data.contextAnaRisk:
General Considerations

MyPrint is a print shop, which has 150 employees. It has a variety of technology and possibilities of printing (rotary press, offset, calligraphy, laser, etc ...) which give a lot of different services and clients from many differents sectors.
Firstly, the company is not targeting any certification; it only wants to know its maturity about information security domain. Later, it will be easier to know which investments to make satisfying the requirements of the financial sector.

Risk management approach

MyPrint does not have any formal processes for the risks management. This first analysis iteration is their move into the information risks, and it has the wish to focus to their core buisness, without getting too much into technical details.

Basic criteria

Risk evaluation criteria must consider at least the financial sector regulation. The corporate image is an essential criterion to exist in this competitive market.

Scope and boundaries

The analysis must focus on the production of the main site. As the others are replica of a moderate size, recommendation would apply to them if necessary.
data.contextGestRisk:
MyPrint has no specialist that could work in the information security field. 
The NC3 consultant will perform a risk analysis using an optimized model. His main contact will be M. Schmidt, leader of the IT department. 
He will nedd to organize all the interviews, which are necessary for the mission, and will give all the needed resources. 
M. Schmidt should be aware and trained to take the lead of the risk management in MyPrint.
data.synthThreat:
The most important safety criterion is the availability of departments. 
The data handled so far are not at all sensitive as they are generally intended for publication (brochures, weeklies, business cards, etc...).
On the other hand, in the future, the manipulation of banking data will completely change the situation and confidentiality will be crucial for certain production chains. 
MyPrint must maintain its brand image, and trust must be earned from the banking sector. 
The table below shows threats that have required particular attention.
